<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="27" pageId="1" pageNumber="26" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1925,2032]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1436,152,858]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="27" pageId="1" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,303,1925,1951]" pageId="1" pageNumber="26">Description.</emphasis>
Male. Length of each forewing 4.0 mm. General color, in alcohol, pale yellow; head and dorsum of thorax with golden setae, antennae stramineous, wings light brown with light yellow setae, legs stramineous with setae dark brown. Male genitalia. Sternum IX short, trapezoidal, anterior margin slightly excavated, and wide posteriorly (
<figureCitation box="[406,477,152,178]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="1.[151,269,1661,1685]" captionTargetBox="[174,1415,452,1628]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[162,1425,419,1652]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. Cernotina odonta sp. nov. (1) male genitalia, left lateral; (2) tergum X, and ventromesal lobe of the preanal appendages, dorsal; (3) sternum IX, and inferior appendages, ventral; (4) phallus, left lateral. Scale = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/184494/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">
Fig. 
<number box="[461,477,152,178]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
). Tergum X membranous, divided into 
<number box="[937,952,152,178]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" value="2.0">2</number>
lobes tapering to apex, with fine setae on all surfaces (
<figureCitation box="[301,373,192,218]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="1.[151,269,1661,1685]" captionTargetBox="[174,1415,452,1628]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[162,1425,419,1652]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. Cernotina odonta sp. nov. (1) male genitalia, left lateral; (2) tergum X, and ventromesal lobe of the preanal appendages, dorsal; (3) sternum IX, and inferior appendages, ventral; (4) phallus, left lateral. Scale = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/184494/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">
Fig. 
<number box="[356,373,192,218]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
). Preanal appendages with dorsolateral lobes apparently absent (
<figureCitation box="[1136,1250,192,218]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="1.[151,269,1661,1685]" captionTargetBox="[174,1415,452,1628]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[162,1425,419,1652]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. Cernotina odonta sp. nov. (1) male genitalia, left lateral; (2) tergum X, and ventromesal lobe of the preanal appendages, dorsal; (3) sternum IX, and inferior appendages, ventral; (4) phallus, left lateral. Scale = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/184494/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Figs. 1, 2</figureCitation>
); and with ventromesal lobes simple, curved inward, and each bearing stout dark spine apically (
<figureCitation box="[1110,1223,232,258]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="1.[151,269,1661,1685]" captionTargetBox="[174,1415,452,1628]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[162,1425,419,1652]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. Cernotina odonta sp. nov. (1) male genitalia, left lateral; (2) tergum X, and ventromesal lobe of the preanal appendages, dorsal; (3) sternum IX, and inferior appendages, ventral; (4) phallus, left lateral. Scale = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/184494/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Figs. 1, 2</figureCitation>
). Inferior appendages elongate (longer than tergum X), longitudinally concave along internal face, bearing fine setae on all surfaces and each with 
<number box="[437,452,312,338]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" value="2.0">2</number>
spine-like setae basally; base broad, abruptly narrowed apex curved inward with internal margin excavated; basodorsal lobe short, tooth-like, partially fused with main body of inferior appendage, bearing 
<number box="[387,402,392,418]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" value="4.0">4</number>
spine-like setae in internal margin, apical margin dark and strongly sclerotized (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="1.[151,269,1661,1685]" captionTargetBox="[174,1415,452,1628]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[162,1425,419,1652]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. Cernotina odonta sp. nov. (1) male genitalia, left lateral; (2) tergum X, and ventromesal lobe of the preanal appendages, dorsal; (3) sternum IX, and inferior appendages, ventral; (4) phallus, left lateral. Scale = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/184494/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Figs. 1, 3</figureCitation>
). Phallus tubular, without distinct phallicata sclerite or spines internally, but bearing internal rows of protuberances with sclerotized apices (
<figureCitation box="[543,616,472,498]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="1.[151,269,1661,1685]" captionTargetBox="[174,1415,452,1628]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[162,1425,419,1652]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. Cernotina odonta sp. nov. (1) male genitalia, left lateral; (2) tergum X, and ventromesal lobe of the preanal appendages, dorsal; (3) sternum IX, and inferior appendages, ventral; (4) phallus, left lateral. Scale = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/184494/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">
Fig. 
<number box="[598,616,472,498]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="27" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,152,858]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,318,511,537]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[326,532,512,537]" class="Insecta" family="Polycentropodidae" genus="Cernotina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="odonta" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[326,532,512,537]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">Cernotina odonta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[540,632,511,537]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[540,632,511,537]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is a very distinctive species and perhaps it is related to 
<taxonomicName authority="Flint, 1971" authorityName="Flint" authorityYear="1971" class="Insecta" family="Polycentropodidae" genus="Cernotina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="compressa">
<emphasis box="[1278,1297,512,537]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1312,1436,512,537]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">compressa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Flint" box="[151,286,552,578]" pageId="2" pageNumber="33" refString="Flint, O. S., Jr. (1971) Studies of Neotropical caddisflies, XII: Rhyacophilidae, Glossosomatidae, Philopotamidae, and Psychomyiidae from the Amazon basin (Trichoptera). Amazoniana, 3, 1 - 67." type="journal article" year="1971">
Flint, 
<number box="[225,286,552,578]" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" value="1971.0">1971</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, as indicated by the short basodorsal lobe broadly fused with the main body of each inferior appendage. The new species differs from 
<taxonomicName box="[640,798,592,618]" class="Insecta" family="Polycentropodidae" genus="Cernotina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="compressa">
<emphasis box="[640,659,592,617]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[674,798,592,617]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="27">compressa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and other species of the genus by the inferior appendages each being longitudinally concave along its internal face with a notch on the internal apex and each having its basodorsal lobe short, tooth-like, largely fused with the appendage and with spine-like mesal setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
